Even tho I have my own website, Dethrosevintage.com, I still have a small amount of remaining inventory on Etsy. Etsy is back at gaslighting their sellers into believing their fees were 5% now going to 6.5%, this is FALSE. For the past year, Etsys fees are actually 12.5% from every single sale. They mask these as separate charges so there is only one fee labeled “transaction fee” which is 6.5%…but then followed by that is another fee labeled “sale fee” at 3%, & “shipping fee” at 3%. Totaling 12.5%. Now if you sell something from their forced google ads then you can then expect it to then total 15% taken for their marketing service. All extremely unfair and deceptive to small business owners trying to maintain a live-able profit margin.

So…because of this on going draining of our profits to line the pocket of yet another corporation, I’m offering to match the current sale prices on Etsy if purchased directly through my website or Venmo. See something currently listed on Etsy and I will match that price ONLY if purchased through my website or Venmo. This will save me 10% of Etsy’s deceptive fees taken from small business owners. Please DM or Email me to adjust price and purchase. This goes for only items listed on Etsy! Thank you and please share!

Cleaning vintage this morning took all morning but worth it. I found this 1960s stunning crepe dress in the summer of 2021. Cover in yellow water stains, I put it in my “to do” pile all us sellers have, and there it sit for two years. I took it out and started a diluted bleach treatment to each spot. Then realized how yellowed the white square all were and spent the morning treating each square. Here’s the before and after, you can see how the white it so much whiter. 

I dedicate this post to the nonsense being posted about what an “easy job” us females have, just to buy cheap and flip to become rich. This dress was found for $25 at a flea market. I had it dry cleaned ($10), which did nothing to remove the yellowing and odor. It took me 4 hours this morning to spot treat each individual square. Then rinsed, laid flat to dry to insure no color bleed and I will then steam her back into shape, sew the buttons back on the back that I removed to prevent any damage. This is all in a day for one piece. And I will sell it accordingly to its worth and my own. 

Mistakes are made, sure, some sellers are dishonest, sure. But what’s happening are blanket statements generalizing a huge community of honest and ethical female run businesses, not just dishonest ones. This job is not easy. You do not just buy a dress for cheap and turn it over for a $100 or more profit…that is an extreme case and rarity. It takes a Looooooooooong list of expenses to run a business that honestly is a struggle and daily hustle to turn a livable profit these days. To spout off hateful rhetoric to consumers who don’t know any better or aren’t informed with no factual knowledge of running a sustainable vintage, not thrift, business, is not doing any good for the customer or small business communities that are what actually make a neighborhood thrive. Thrift stores and shelters that are for the poor or needy I’ve volunteered for and continue to do so, do NOT ACCEPT, vintage clothing. They do not accept clothing older than the last two decades normally because that is not what actual people in need want or need. So vintage sellers are not stealing from them. Be kind, be informed, and know your market.

Inspired by @shopladyberet’s post about inclusivity with sizing in the vintage community, I wanted to share a few things regarding the topic. 

While larger sizes in vintage, even medium sizes, can be hard to find in Midcentury and older clothing, it’s important we try our hardest to include them in our shops. The fashion industry has a long history of excluding larger shapes, and fat-phobic views in beauty standards. The vintage community has been just as bad. I see shops that tend to carry a 24”-27” waist, and I ask myself “are they just selling their own clothing or do they refuse to buy larger pieces??” Let’s be honest, this absurd beauty standard is alive and well in fashion, which should be abolished. Thin does not always equal beauty or healthy for that matter. I’m ecstatic every time I find larger sizes, because I know my clients are wanting it. Every single body should feel vintage fashion is also for them. You’ll notice that Xs/S sit for waaaay longer in my shop. Because Med-XXXL often sells quick! Why? Because that is truly the real standard of sizing. 

For those new to my shop, any hate speech is not tolerated. That includes self hate speech about your own body. Every single body shape and size is beautiful and worthy of being included. When you shop my shop and see mostly Xs/s left, it’s because the Med-XXXL have sold. But don’t fret, I will always try to provide it as much as I can find it! So here’s a few slides of 29” (which I know is still on the small end) all the way to 42” waists currently available. 44” and up waist sizes go quick, so definitely don’t hesitate to email me your measurements and what you’re looking for and I can email you when those sizes and styles arrive in the shop! 💋❤️ If you are interested in a piece in any of the slides, DM me for a 15% off discount code 💋 Tag your favorite inclusive vintage shops below! No gate keeping here!

Waking up to the news articles about Pamela Anderson being brave and courageous for going to events with a clean face left me feeling inspired but also livid. Having a clean face shouldn't be an act of courage or a revolution, but it is. It is, because women are taught from a very young age, our faces are something that needs to hide, needs improvement. Yet men walk around without a mask everyday. That's how you know the patriarchy despises women's natural beauty & strength. It taught us to be ashamed of our faces & bodies, enhance them with paint or plastic. I don’t judge those who do enhance their face. Having this opinion that women feel that they have to stay young or “made up” isn’t based on judgment, it’s based on society. I wish society, men, other women could have allowed us the freedom to just exist in our skin comfortably as we are. Let us be intelligent, sexy, beautiful, or simply loved when we are young or old. Fat, skinny, small noses, big noses, thin lips, full lips, soft skin, rough skin, wrinkles, cellulite, breasts of all sizes, hairless, hairy, just let us love ourselves and LIVE. 

Love Pamela and always have. She stopped getting Botox, fillers and using much makeup, embracing who she is and I wish she could've done this long ago for herself. I hope others take note, including myself. I've never left the house without at least concealer and lipstick. I’ve been ashamed since I was like 13 for having dark circles and puffy eyes in the morning.  Hating what I see in the mirror because I’m told to by society’s ever changing high standards for women. Beauty shouldn't be defined by trends, or what others deem as such. Beauty should be defined by integrity, sense of self, humor, the strength in our eyes. So I’m going to try and take Pamela’s advice and choose life-ing instead of viewing it as aging. 

The last few years I have felt more joyful because I’ve leaned into relaxing, living moment to moment. You find more happiness & freedom in living day to day instead of trying to predict or expect so much for the future. I have no expectations for my life or face. I just want to enjoy & love both while I’m here. I think that alone will keep us young.
